It is easy to one man bleed. Just start with the shortest line and loosen
the bleed screw and turn it in until it just starts to seat and back off so
it doesnt touch. Slowly pump the pedal without using full strokes. Push in
slowly and return a little faster, then wait. Repeat until you have clean
fluid running out. What you are trying to do is have the return springs
push fluid enough to overcome negative pressure to pull air back in the
bleed screw. After you bleed all four wheels the pedal will start to feel
solid. Repeat and you will have it done as good as having someone help. Dont
try and use the siphon line in brake fluid. You want to push all the fluid
through the master cylinder and flush any impurities out at the wheel. Never
having someone to help I have used this way and dont bother anyone to help
anymore. It will take a little time to master it if you are not real
familiar with all the internal workings of a brake system. Make sure the
master cylinder is bled first before doing the wheels. It can be done the
same way. Bleed screw(if equipped) or loosen line.

